         <tbody><tr class=3D"replica" name=3D"intro">
          <td style=3D"padding-bottom: 36px;">
           <p style=3D"margin: 0; color: #000000; font-size: 16px; line-hei=
ght: 30px; margin-top: 20px; margin-bottom: 0;">Welcome back to Dry Powder.=
 I=E2=80=99m <b>Bill Cohan</b>.<br/><br/>On Thursday morning, as I was read=
ing through <b>Robert Gibbs</b>=E2=80=99s carefully crafted Warner Bros. Di=
scovery press release announcing that <b>David Zaslav</b> was reorganizing =
the company and essentially following the same strategic path that his fren=
emy <b>Brian Roberts</b> had started down a month earlier at Comcast, two <=
i>particularly</i> intriguing sentences stood out to me. In today=E2=80=99s=
 issue, a close look at what that document reveals about WBD=E2=80=99s plan=
s.  <br/><br/><i>But first=E2=80=A6</i><br/><br/></p><ul style=3D"margin:0;=
color:#000000;font-size:16px;line-height:30px;margin-top:0;margin-bottom:0;=
list-style-type:square;mso-special-format:bullet"><li><i>Jonah and the whal=
e</i>: A few days after it looked like BuzzFeed=E2=80=99s creditors might f=
orce the =E2=80=9Cgoing concern=E2=80=9D into a debt restructuring=E2=80=94=
or
<i>worse</i>, bankruptcy=E2=80=94the publicly traded digital media company =
seems to have pulled a rabbit out of its hat, staving off financial disaste=
r, at least for now. On December 12, BuzzFeed announced it had consummated =
a deal with a group of investors, led by funds affiliated with <b>George So=
ros</b>, to sell its First We Feast brand=E2=80=94the food blog turned digi=
tal media phenomenon, featuring the celebrity-stacked <i>Hot Ones</i> talk =
show=E2=80=94for $82.5 million in cash. Those proceeds, along with the $54 =
million on BuzzFeed=E2=80=99s balance sheet, as of September 30, gives the =
company some $136.5 million in cash, enough to pay off the $124 million in =
8.5 percent convertible notes due 2026 that posed an urgent existential dil=
emma for the company. (For more on BuzzFeed=E2=80=99s high-wire week, you c=
an revisit my previous dissertation <u><a href=3D"https://email.puck.news/e=
/c/eyJlbWFpbF9pZCI6ImRnVDJ4Z1lEQUt2UktxclJLZ0dUektoZGV1TzR6eG11T0xXT2VJND0i=
LCJocmVmIjoiaHR0cHM6Ly9wdWNrLm5ld3MvbmV3c2xldHRlcl9jb250ZW50L3RoZS1uZXctbGl=
uYS1raGFuLWJ1enpmZWVkLWJhbmtydXB0Y3ktY29uY2VybnMtc290aGVieXMtcmVzdHJ1Y3R1cm=
luZy8_dXRtX2NhbXBhaWduPURyeStQb3dkZXIrLStTVUJTQ1JJQkVSUyslMjgxMiUyRjE1JTJGM=
jQlMjlcdTAwMjZ1dG1fY29udGVudD1EcnkrUG93ZGVyKy0rU1VCU0NSSUJFUlMrJTI4MTIlMkYx=
MSUyRjI0JTI5XHUwMDI2dXRtX21lZGl1bT1lbWFpbF9hY3Rpb25cdTAwMjZ1dG1fc291cmNlPWN=
1c3RvbWVyLmlvXHUwMDI2dXRtX3Rlcm09ZjZjNjA2MTdkYTQyYWJkMTJhIiwiaW50ZXJuYWwiOi=
JmNmM2MDYxN2RhNDJhYmQxMmEiLCJsaW5rX2lkIjoyMDE4OTA5fQ/9b0c028ed01ce99ca0be4c=
6e4462dab64cd69b1ae406c6b643c027e5112717fe" style=3D"color:#d40000;text-dec=
oration:none;font-weight:bold" class=3D"sdf">here</a></u>.)<br/><br/>Accord=
ing to a new filing with the Securities and Exchange Commission, BuzzFeed w=
ill use $75.6 million of the First We Feast proceeds to redeem a majority o=
f the notes=E2=80=94a transaction that is slated to close on December 18. S=
eparately, the company=E2=80=99s filing indicated that it had reached an ag=
reement with other noteholders to buy $12 million of their notes for 100 ce=
nts on the dollar, plus accrued interest. That transaction closed December =
11. After all is said and done, some $30 million of principal will still be=
 outstanding and allowed to be outstanding, per a new agreement reached wit=
h the noteholders. <br/><br/>From what I can glean from the public filings,=
 BuzzFeed will now have nearly $50 million in cash on
hand and the $30 million of debt, making for a very favorable net debt posi=
tion, below zero. Its =E2=80=9Cadjusted EBITDA=E2=80=9D for the nine months=
 of 2024 ended September 30 was around $2 million, which would barely cover=
 the $2.5 million of annual interest payments on that still-outstanding $30=
 million of debt. (This is where that $50 million of cash the company has w=
ill come in handy.) <br/><br/>So while an existential crisis has been avert=
ed, challenges aplenty remain for C.E.O. <b>Jonah Peretti</b>. BuzzFeed=E2=
=80=99s =E2=80=9Cadjusted EBITDA=E2=80=9D could use a boost, especially sin=
ce it=E2=80=99s not known how much EBITDA, if any, First We Feast was contr=
ibuting to the mix of BuzzFeed, HuffPost, etcetera. (It must have been subs=
tantial for the new investors to have paid $82.5 million.) In a separate pr=
ess release, BuzzFeed issued guidance for its fourth quarter, ending Decemb=
er, of revenue between $54 million and $58 million and =E2=80=9Cadjusted EB=
ITDA=E2=80=9D between $4 million and $9 million. <br/><br/>That
sounds like good news, right? Well, for whatever reasons, the market didn=
=E2=80=99t like the deal. (Maybe analysts and investors know that <i>Hot On=
es</i> was BuzzFeed=E2=80=99s golden goose?) Anyway, BuzzFeed=E2=80=99s sto=
ck was down nearly 13 percent on Thursday and another 5 percent on Friday, =
giving the company a market value of $130 million=E2=80=94about one -ninth =
of what it was worth after its first day as a public company back in Decemb=
er 2021.</li></ul>
          </td>
